issues.title: Coil Pack Failure
issues.description: Ignition coil packs fail prematurely, causing misfires and poor engine performance. This is a known issue across the DB9 range, particularly affecting cylinders 4 and 8.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed coil packs with updated versions. Often requires replacement of spark plugs as well.
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance and using quality fuel. Replace spark plugs at recommended intervals.

issues.title: Clutch Pressure Plate Failure
issues.description: The clutch pressure plate on manual transmission models develops cracks and fails, leading to clutch slippage and eventual complete failure.
issues.fix_description: Complete clutch replacement including pressure plate, disc, and release bearing. Often requires gearbox removal.
issues.prevention: Avoid riding the clutch, proper shifting technique, and regular clutch fluid changes.

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: The door handle mechanisms, particularly the exterior handles, fail due to worn plastic components and cable stretching, making doors difficult or impossible to open.
issues.fix_description: Replace door handle mechanism and cables. May require door panel removal and handle assembly replacement.
issues.prevention: Gentle operation of door handles and regular lubrication of moving parts.

issues.title: Touchtronic Transmission Valve Body Issues
issues.description: The ZF 6HP26 automatic transmission develops valve body problems, causing harsh shifting, delayed engagement, and transmission faults.
issues.fix_description: Rebuild or replace valve body assembly. May require complete transmission rebuild in severe cases.
issues.prevention: Regular transmission fluid changes every 30,000 miles and avoiding aggressive driving.

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Splitter Damage
issues.description: The front carbon fiber splitter is prone to damage from road debris, speed bumps, and low ground clearance, causing cracking and delamination.
issues.fix_description: Replace damaged carbon fiber splitter with new OEM or aftermarket unit.
issues.prevention: Careful driving over speed bumps and rough surfaces, consider splitter protection.

issues.title: Cooling System Thermostat Failure
issues.description: The engine thermostat fails, causing overheating or overcooling issues. The V12 engine runs hot and thermostat failure can lead to serious engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace thermostat and housing assembly. Flush cooling system and replace coolant.
issues.prevention: Regular cooling system maintenance and coolant changes every 3-4 years.

issues.title: Rear Differential Mount Failure
issues.description: The rear differential mounts deteriorate and fail, causing vibration, clunking noises, and poor handling, particularly under acceleration.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn differential mounts with new or uprated units. May require subframe removal.
issues.prevention: Avoid hard launches and aggressive driving. Regular inspection of drivetrain mounts.

issues.title: ECU Water Damage
issues.description: Engine and transmission ECUs are located in areas prone to water ingress, particularly from sunroof drains and windshield leaks, causing expensive electronic failures.
issues.fix_description: Repair or replace damaged ECUs. Address water ingress sources such as blocked drains or faulty seals.
issues.prevention: Regular inspection and clearing of sunroof drains. Keep vehicle in covered parking when possible.

issues.title: Oil Leak from Cam Cover Gaskets
issues.description: The V12 engine develops oil leaks from the cam cover gaskets, particularly on the rear bank which is difficult to access and expensive to repair.
issues.fix_description: Replace cam cover gaskets and associated seals. Rear bank requires significant disassembly.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with quality oil and filters. Avoid overrevving when engine is cold.

issues.title: Suspension Bushing Deterioration
issues.description: Suspension bushings, particularly the front control arm bushings, deteriorate prematurely causing poor handling, vibration, and uneven tire wear.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn suspension bushings with OEM or uprated polyurethane units. Wheel alignment required.
issues.prevention: Avoid potholes and rough roads. Regular suspension inspections and prompt replacement of worn components.

editorial.tagline: Naturally aspirated V12 grand touring perfection
editorial.hero_blurb: The DB9 represents Aston Martin's golden era of naturally aspirated V12 grand touring. Built on the revolutionary VH platform, it combines stunning design with a magnificent 6.0-liter V12 that defines automotive soul.
editorial.essence: The DB9 is the quintessential modern Aston Martin, blending British craftsmanship with sophisticated engineering. Its naturally aspirated V12 delivers pure, linear power alongside one of the most beautiful exhaust notes ever created.
editorial.heritage: Launched in 2004 as Aston Martin's flagship GT, the DB9 revived the legendary DB lineage that began with the DB4. Built on the advanced VH (Vertical/Horizontal) aluminum platform, it marked Aston Martin's renaissance under Ford ownership and established the design language that would define the brand for decades.
editorial.design_philosophy: Ian Callum and Henrik Fisker created a timeless design that balanced aggression with elegance, featuring the signature swan doors, muscular haunches, and distinctive grille that made every DB9 instantly recognizable as an Aston Martin.
editorial.motorsport_history: While primarily a road car, the DB9 spawned the DBR9 race car that competed successfully in GT1 championships worldwide, including victories at Le Mans and the FIA GT Championship, proving the platform's performance credentials.
editorial.engine_character: The 6.0L V12 is a masterpiece of naturally aspirated engineering, delivering 450-510hp depending on year with silky smooth power delivery and an intoxicating crescendo that builds to 7000rpm redline.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 6-speed ZF automatic (later Touchtronic 2) provides smooth, refined shifts in comfort mode but can be surprisingly aggressive when pushed, though it lacks the immediacy of modern dual-clutch units.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The VH aluminum spaceframe provides excellent rigidity while the adaptive damping keeps the ride compliant for grand touring duties yet composed enough for spirited driving on winding roads.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulically assisted steering offers good weight and feedback, providing confidence-inspiring precision without being overly heavy, perfectly suited to the car's grand touring character.
editorial.brake_confidence: Brembo brakes provide strong, progressive stopping power with good pedal feel, though sustained track use can reveal thermal limitations typical of GT cars from this era.
editorial.sound_signature: The naturally aspirated V12 produces one of the greatest automotive soundtracks ever recorded - a deep, cultured rumble at idle that transforms into a spine-tingling wail as revs climb toward redline.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving enthusiasts who appreciate naturally aspirated engines, handcrafted luxury, and timeless design. Perfect for those wanting a special occasion car that can comfortably cover long distances in supreme style.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Daily commuters, track-focused drivers seeking ultimate performance, or those prioritizing fuel economy and modern infotainment systems over character and craftsmanship.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with complete service history, as the V12 requires careful attention. Later models offer improved reliability and features, but all DB9s represent exceptional value for naturally aspirated V12 grand touring.

LIGHTING: Golden hour sunlight streaming through large industrial windows. Warm color temperature. Cinematic depth.

TECHNICAL: Magazine-quality automotive photography. Photorealistic, no CGI look. No people, no text, no watermarks, no logos, no license plates.
